In C, memory deallocation is done using the `free()` function, which is found in the `stdlib.h` header file. The `free()` function is used to release memory that was previously allocated using memory allocation functions like `malloc()`, `calloc()`, or `realloc()`.

Here's a brief example of allocating and deallocating memory using `malloc()` and `free()`:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    int *arr;
    int n, i;

    printf("Enter the number of elements: ");
    scanf("%d", &n);

    arr = (int*) malloc(n * sizeof(int));

    if (arr == NULL) {
        printf("Memory allocation failed.\n");
        return 1;
    }

    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        printf("Enter element %d: ", i + 1);
        scanf("%d", &arr[i]);
    }

    // ... Do some processing with the array ...

    // Deallocate memory
    free(arr);

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, memory is allocated using `malloc()` for an integer array, and then released using `free()` after its usage. Remember to always free up memory when it is no longer needed to prevent memory leaks in your program.
